< Review>
As a displaced former resident of both NJ and IL, pizza and sandwiches are a sensitive topic for me.  The pizza here is good.  Not great, but decent.  I don't say that often.  For now, they have won my business till I find something better, presuming i'm in the mood for ny-style.

I tried a combination (pepperoni, sausage, olive mushroom and something else...) and a shrimp pesto pizza.  Both were pretty good though if I go back i'll probably get lesser toppings.  One thing i've noticed about all ny style pizza's here (ie, not in ny) is their crusts just aren't quite right.  The problem is made worse by the grease in the toppings which saturates the thiner crusts.  I don't really know why this never seems an issue out east... but i definitely notice this across the board here in CA.  That said, this crust held up well, but still suffered the problem.

Their prices are great relative to the food volume, and it feels like a ny pizza place, small cozy and not really meant for you to stay in.  Consider calling ahead and getting it to go.  A pie takes about 10-15min to cook up.</Review>

<user_name>Tim W</user_name><review>Confirming the swing has been removed: it appears the chains were cut about halfway down. There are "habitat restoration" signs placed all around the area. This "hidden" vista became too popular (this Maps pin is one example of that) and the natural habitat has been trampled to slick dirt. I feel bad for the UCSD students who weren't here to enjoy it one last time.

EDIT: Just want to add a note that this "on-again, off-again" nature of the swing is apparently pretty common. Until UCSD permanently fences the area, the likelihood that a swing will be present is a toss-up.< /review>< rate>

< review>
I'm very worried by the number of people congregating here from many different places, including children and groups of 10+, as well as mountain bikers who are destroying significant parts of the trail. Very few people appear to be making any effort to distance. Last year the end of the trail was a field of flowers, today it is completely torn up. Please stay home, and if you are going to come here for a walk, please no groups larger than 2 or 3.<//review>

He went through each finding and discussed the outliers (ones that were outside the preferred ranges) in more detail than the "in-range" results. He offered suggestions for ways to improve the outliers and we agreed to make changes to my diet and to take supplements designed to target certain deficiencies. We will meet again in a few months to monitor specific results/outcomes. I was very happy with the approach.

Dr. Larson is intelligent; charming and has a warm nature to his demeanor that lowers any stress or drama in the discussion of his findings. He is clearly an expert in his field and passionate about his work. I would certainly recommend him to anyone seeking to better understand their health. < text>
I am convinced I am one of the most complex patients and it has been due to being put off by doctors for all of my adult life especially dealing with mostly military treatment facilities. I have good insurance, but the doctors that took my insurance were obviously overwhelmed, had a very limited timetable of 15 minutes or less, and I never felt took the time to look at me as a whole and figure out why this were the way they were. Also moving a lot due to my husband's career, my medical history is a piecemeal of records of almost two decades. It got to a point where my anxiety was at an all time high and depression due to that was creeping up, and I just got to the point where I was exhausted. I was exhausted of doctors either patching up one leak, only for another to spring, or telling me it's all in my head (which having severe anxiety I know some of it is in fact in my head), or just shrugging their shoulders. From the moment I walked in, the medical assistant was so warm and friendly and funny and made everything so easy. My sky high anxiety I had driving there was lowered considerably just because I felt safe in that space. I was worried before seeing the doctor that oh man, he is going to think I'm crazy, I've got this list of things that I don't understand going on. But again making it to the point where you feel like you aren't living any kind of life worth living because of the way you physically and mentally feel, the only option I had was to seek out medical care out of my pocket. After reading all the reviews prior to coming, I really put all my eggs in one basket. I am so glad I did. Even after the first visit, I got on my car to go home and just cried because the relief you feel of having one single provider take time with you, listen to you, understand what you are saying, and say we can fix these things after nearly 20 years of frustration and disappointment and dead ends is extremely overwhelming. If you are like me and have "good insurance" (well...Tricare), and you are debating whether it is worth it to maybe give a little more for your healthcare, do it...please, do it. It IS worth it even after one visit. I cannot thank this doctor and staff enough. I am so ready to get my whole body and mind to be the best it can be, and after leaving this appointment, I have no doubt I will be able to with Dr. Larson and his staff's help.< /text>

<user_id>101410663803225749589< /user_id>< Name>
Peter Petey Pete< /Name>
<Time>1504685377873<//Time><Rating>5</Rating>< review>
Hotdogs and Beer!

You'll be lucky to find a bar where they offer a single hotdog on their menu. This place has 5 different ones! With a choice of classic dog or gourmet sausage, along with many other hotdog centric appetizers, there is bound to be something to satisfy your hotdog craving. They also offer other traditional bar food as well.

I ordered the Sonoran and Carnitas classic with a side of tots. Both were great but don't order two. One is plenty to get full from. The toppings are served high atop a large classic style dog wrapped in bacon placed in soft grilled bun. The bacon could probably have been cooked a little longer for my preference. The bun was perfect, almost as soft as a Hawaiian roll.

The tots were great! Really crispy/crunchy and seasoned with a spiced fine salt.

Service was very friendly, attentive and fast.

I will definitely return to try their gourmet sausage and a pint of beer during a ballgame.<//review>

<Pics>None</Pics>< Review>
After being with the same veterinary clinic for nearly 14 years, we took a leap of faith with Emeryville Vet Hospital when we adopted a kitten. They are conveniently located to us (only a 5mns drive) as opposed to 25mns across town. And wow, we were pleasantly surprised: the team is very responsive, attentive even when you can only drop off your pet and no access to the facilities. On our first visit, the doctor came out and introduced herself (which was great when you start a brand new relationship). The cost of services are reasonable. Hard to comment on how your pet is being handled since you are not in the room with the vet or the tech, but our pet did not seem to be distraught at all - so one can only assume that all went well during his visits.</Review>

< Review>
If I could leave a 0 star rating here I absolutely would. Admittedly getting a puppy during COVID meant our options were limited as many of the vets we first reached out to were either not taking new patients or were under 4 week plus waits to get an appointment. On our first appointment with Dr. Anderson she did not bother to come out to introduce herself. Both of my parents are vets and this is standard practice even during Covid when a new client is bringing in their pet. During our second visit we waited at the curb after letting them know we were there for an hour, only to find out during our last visit, today. The vet did not see our pup but it was considered a "tech" visit and the vet techs handle that solo. So we waited an hour to see a tech for shots. Today, despite flagging a potential allergic reaction our pup was having  pre shots the techs gave our pup shots. After calling my mom and dad for whether this was sound practice,  they both confirmed they never have only the tech manage visit at their respective clinics and would not have given shots to a dog showing signs of an allergic reaction as she was. My vet visit today concluded with the tech asking me to write down my concerns and "maybe" the vet would give me a call. I am planning to report this to the board of vet medicine and have requested my records now that her (my dogs) initial shot series is out of the way so that I can find a vet and vet hospital staff that actually cares about their clients well being and customer service. If you care about your fur baby, I would highly advise going elsewhere!< /Review>

<userid>101362448159695148995< /userid>< Text>
Pets are family, and my two dogs are my children.

I have two dogs, and I have been taking both to this clinic since Bear was a puppy, so just over 3 years and Leela is about 18 months.

In the beginning, the staff was wonderful, and the vets were so caring -but recently I have had two bad experiences and the most recent happened just yesterday over to today.

Yesterday I brought both dogs for an annual exam and booster shots.  Dr. Anderson reminded me that Leela had a reaction the last time, and recommended that we give her a Benadryl shot prior to booster shots- I agree this is a good idea.

We get home, they both seem fine.  Around 10:30 p.m. Leela stars to balloon up, her poor face is all swollen and she is clearly freaking out.  I first got the paperwork to see if Dr. Anderson left any instruction on what to do, and of course, there was nothing and they were closed.

We then decided to take her to a local Pet Hospital, Sage, and they were wonderful--but pointed out that Leela at 15p should not have had all four shots at once, and especially since she had a reaction once before.  The shots should have been broken up over days to figure out what she was having a reaction to.  They gave her some steroids, and a Benadryl shot and asked me to monitor her for the next two days.

Today, I called Dr. Anderson to express my concerns. I relayed the Sage Dr. concerns and pushed for answers about their practices and She would not take any responsibility and pushed back. I stated Leela should have never had all four shots at once, we should have narrowed down what is causing the reaction.  Her attitude was caviler and borderline careless.

The first incident involved a lot of bad customer service when Leela had to have an emergency spay- I ended up having to take her to a different clinic because they were closed, and their sister clinic by Lake Merit wouldn't make time for us--even though she was bleeding.

There is no way in hell I would take my fur babies back here, If you feel as passionate about being your pets advocate because they have no voice--please take your loved ones somewhere else...</Text>

< username>
Joe Kochanski<//username>
<user>102392675190597310776<//user><review>We had been reasonably happy with the E'ville Vet Hospital up until recently. The most glaring explanation for the downgrade is that Dr. Harper is no longer working at this clinic. That's a HUGE loss since the guy was a no BS, fair, reasonable, pro. It's regrettably to know this now, and helps explain why things have slipped substantially in the last few months. While the technicians are personable and clearly care about the animals' health (2, in particular, are all-stars), no one knows your name or your dogs name, regardless of how many times you have to take your pet in. In this way, they act more as an urgent care clinic for animals as opposed to a 'primary care' vet office. Further evidence of this is that when taking our puppy in, everyone was totally confused about what treatments were required - to the point that we had to restart an entire treatment cycle that kept our puppy stuck in the house for more than a month longer than should have been necessary. If you don't ask, they won't know what's needed, so you really have to advocate for your animal, unfortunately. The most recent problem is that our dog had a small surgery. When we were still having issues, we tried to get her in, and were told to just do home care. We ended up taking her to a different vet who confirmed our suspicions: the dog had an infection and needed anti-bacterial/anti-fungal treatment. Without this, the dog would have suffered for at least a week. Finally, pricing is not as good as reviews will lead you to believe. You can't go to this vet without paying $100 under any circumstances. At the end of the day, I hate to write a poor review because there are a couple of staffers who don't deserve that, but the operation, on the whole, does. It seems that poor management and lack of leadership are the culprits to what may be the start of EVH's ultimate demise.

October 2020 update: Dr. Harper is now practicing at VetnCare in Alameda. Go there, not because I know much about VetnCare (my only experience with them was a good one), but because that is where the best Vet I've ever encountered practices. Cheers.< /review>< Gmap_id>

< Review>
Needed a classic, subtle - but swaggy hat for a destination wedding in Cuba. Naturally, I ended up getting the "Havana". I followed the size guide provided, but the hat was a bit too tight (to be fair, I fell in between a small/medium - a smedium if you may.) I contacted Ariel - the "fit specialist" -  he advanced and rushed shipped the next size up so I had it in time for the wedding. Easily the best online experience I've had with a return...will buy all my hats here moving forward. Highly recommend! Can't wait for the photos from the wedding rocking this!< /Review>

<review>The only reason I am still here is my agent Raul.  He understands my needs and helps attain them. Third agent was very good but grew his business so big he lost touch with some clients, his staff did not treat me to what I was used too. None<//Pics>
<Resp>{'time': 1581010741199, 'text': 'Thank you for candid feedback, Mr. Alvidrez.  And thank you for your kind words about Raul, the agent that helped you here at our agency. As independent agents, our agency represents over 30 insurance companies. Mercury is one that that we have worked with for 50 years, since our agency started back in 1970. The unfortunate thing is that all companies, not just Mercury, over time need to increase their rates to keep up with inflation, the high cost of repairs and medical expenses, and the ever increasing cost of litigation and lawsuits. We understand your frustration. We are consumers too and like you, we look for the best rate we can get.  As you said, Raul did an excellent job at looking for the best combination of low rates and  coverages adequate to your own situation. In your case, Mercury still offers you the lowest rate we can find you, again from the more than 30 companies we represent.\nI want to personally thank you for being our valued client. <gmapID>0x80d9571089292247:0x26eaf07e05112468</gmapID>< Review>
Hygiene is a big issue in this market. My wife and I have been a customer for some time and our stories started to stockpile. Meat was rotten many times, so we stopped buying from the meat department there. Then cheese was rotten, and we stopped buying cheese. Once I saw a mouse running in the store. So, we stopped buying anything that had their own label and stuck to the imported things. But then we found bugs in the flour many times. We have quit being customers there after we had one complaint and they handled it in the most unprofessional way possible. If you look carefully behind the shelfs, the bathroom and peak into their back areas, you will be disgusted. I recommend Frazier Farms Market which is a couple hundred feet away where you can buy almost the same products. It's a little more expensive, but you can save yourself some stress and health issues.< /Review>

<Text>[Update 2/21/21]  This visit compared to the last two was so much better.  It probably helped that the person behind the deli counter knew who I was and that it was me who left a negative review.  This was evident by her comment at the end of our transaction.  This level of service is what I had gotten used to which was why I was surprised when it tanked the way it did.

Management had reached out to me and stressed that they strive to give their best. They laid out what was going to be done to fix the problem and voila, problem solved.  I probably should've ordered the same sandwich as last time but ehhh I wasn't in the mood for it

Kudos for making customer service a priority.  This is something other stores have let fall on the wayside and fail to recognize they are just hurting themselves by alienating us.

--------------------------------

[1 Star on 2/15/21] It's sad that I have to write a bad review about this place given that I was singing its praises not so long ago.  Unfortunately, two separate incidences in the same department have made me weary.  I didn't report it the first time on here but I did at the store to the front manager because the manager that handles the back had already gone home.  Anyway, my bad experiences take place at the deli counter.  The first incident was back in January.  A woman with black and blond hair was the attendant.  First, it took her more than 5 minutes to recognize she even had customers lining up.  Then when she finally did it was with an attitude.  I figured she was just having a bad day and I ordered my sandwich and side and did some more shopping since it takes them a while to get it together.  I come back for my sandwich 10 minutes later and she's still not finished.  I wait 5 more minutes and she gives me the sandwich but no side.  I had politely asked her to give me a side of antipasto salad I believe it was and she looked as if she wanted to kill me.  So much so that the other customer looked at me and asked me, as the attendant turned to get the container for the side, "What did you do to her?".  I replied, "I just ordered a sandwich."  Then to top it all off which I hadn't noticed until I got home, I got charged $7.99 for the sandwich and $3.99 for the side which was supposed to be included.

Anywho, skip forward to Saturday (2/13).  A new person is behind the deli counter and I order a Tri-Tip Feta sandwich on Foccacia bread.  Right away I noticed the person didn't know what to do, so I told her I'd be back.  I went and purchased some meat.  The guy behind that counter has always been friendly to me but it's busy, so I waited for my turn.  In the meantime, I note that the deli person is taking care of 3 customers while I'm getting my meat.  I go back to the deli counter after getting the meat and now the person is on the interphone, which I'm assuming is to ask for help.  Someone finally shows up and meanwhile 3 other customers are being taken care of.  It took 21 minutes to finish 1 sandwich and to top it off, it was salty as heck.  By the time I got it home, the bread had fallen apart.  It was sooooo sloppy!  Never again will I order anything at the deli counter and if I have another bad experience, I may not return to the store at all.</Text>< pictures>

< time>
1606234316868<//time>
<Review>Overall  a small local market with good prices and convenient deli and bakery. However, poduce can be hit and miss.  Some of it is very good and well stocked such as eggplant,  onions, potatoes, and cucumbers.  But citrus, apples, tomatoes, herbs, and others sometimes give the impression that they were not that fresh even before they were stocked.  Produce typically has some blemishes, which is ok for the price reduction trade-off.  But over ripe or lower quality items will sometimes have you making a trip another market on the way home.

Prices are typically lower than supermarkets for most items.  I have had very good experiences with butcher, bakery, and deli departments. One of the few places to find fresh dark breads.  If you need something for an eastern european or middle eastern meal then this is a great place to shop because of the variety of brands and ingredients.  Bonus points for dried spices, bulk bins, good cheese selection  (several styles of feta) fresh squeezed juices and prepared meals, fresh salads and various fresh dips.< /Review><user_name>Zoyd Wheeler<//user_name><user_id>113054805744397671577</user_id></record>

< user>
100632513839405797964<//user>
<name>Anish Thakkar (Doc Thakkar)<//name><Date>1585419547578</Date><Rate>5<//Rate>< review>
I'm all about this place. Here are the reasons why:

-Vine Ripe is a family-owned business.
-Vine Ripe has super-friendly employees, from the cashiers up front to the deli workers in the back.
-Vine Ripe has obscure middle eastern specialties, ranging from fresh tahini to turkish seasonings.
-Vine Ripe has a ton of POG (Passion Orange Guava): best juice ever.
-Vine Ripe is CHEAP: think $.99/lb chicken drumsticks, $.40 avocados, $.99/lb serrano peppers.

If you want the charm of an international market with the produce prices of a farmer's market, this is your place! Also, they have hot prepared food which they sell by the pound in the back, which I would have tried had I not just eaten dinner. Definitely give this place a shot - just make sure that everything is at peak freshness! 5 stars well earned.< /review>

< Review>
I recently started coming back here because my grocery bill from Trader's and Sprouts was astronomical. So now I buy my produce, chicken and beef here for about half. For a while the produce was really bad, but I think they have new management because it's much fresher.

We got some New York steaks here for dinner and I was expecting a mediocre cut, but it was actually really good and tender. Great for ground beef and lamb. They have real butchers too, if you're into that.

I still have to hit up TJs for some stuff, but this is my new go-to place for produce.< /Review>

< Review>
Great selection of products from around the world. Lots of Middle Eastern staples and speclity items available.
They have an intesting /offbeat selection of eastern European and  Russian beer and wine.
Their produce is top notch at excellent prices.
Their meat department is even better. They sell great quality halal meat at prices that are Competitive with the big chains . ( Look for sales)  .
Try the kefta. If you've never had kefta it's a seasoned ground meat traditionally made from lamb. Today most of it is made with ground beef, with or without ground lamb. The kefta at Vine Ripe has lamb. It's the best around.

Making kefta is as easy as makeing hamburger s</Review>
